<div class="articleBodyText section">




<div class="component article-body-text    " data-test="article-body-text">
  
  

	

	
	

	
	



  
  
    <p>The best clothes steamers are shortcuts to <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/recommended/home/best-steam-irons/">ironing</a>, straightening out creases within minutes while generally using <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/recommended/home/best-energy-saving-products/">less electricity</a>. Whereas ironing boards can take up space in a small home, steamer irons just require somewhere to hang your garment and a nearby plug.</p><p>Theyre not just for occasional use: the best <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/style/hand-steamers-new-must-have-why/">handheld clothes steamers</a> can hold enough water to get through a few items of clothes before needing refilling, while freestanding clothes steamers can manage whole laundry loads. Cordless clothes steamers would seem to be the next step, but theyve not yet hit the shelves in the UK.</p><p>Clothes steamers are multi-functional pieces of kit, too. They can be used for cleaning curtains and upholstery, killing the majority of bacteria and removing stale odours. They let you de-crease <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/interiors/home/the-best-duvets-for-a-good-nights-sleep/">duvets</a> without removing them from the bed and, if you have a work shirt that needs a little freshen-up, steaming it is far better for the environment than throwing it into the <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/interiors/home/best-washing-machines-fresh-clean-clothes/">washing machine</a> and <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/interiors/home/best-tumble-dryer/">tumble dryer</a>. (Talking of which, <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/recommended/home/best-heated-clothes-airer/">heated airers</a> are a newfound godsend for the energy-aware.)</p><p>You can find our full reviews of the best clothes steamers <a class="ck-custom-link" href="#best-clothes-steamers">below</a>, followed by some tips from fashion experts on how to use them. But if youre in a hurry, heres a quick look at our top five:</p><h2 class="u-heading-size-medium u-heading-style-normal">The best clothes steamers, at a glance</h2><ul><li><strong>Best overall </strong>- <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Russell-Hobbs-28370-Clothes-Steamer/dp/B0B2DMM78J/ref&#61;asc_df_B0B2DMM78J/?tag&#61;telegraphaffiliate-21&amp;ascsubtag&#61;customid-21" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Russell Hobbs Steam Genie 2-in-1 Garment Steamer</a></li><li><strong>Best value clothes steamer </strong>- <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Cadrim-Clothes-Handheld-Vertical-Powerful/dp/B08XB82VXY/ref&#61;asc_df_B08XB82VXY/?tag&#61;telegraphaffiliate-21&amp;ascsubtag&#61;customid-21&amp;th&#61;1" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Cadrim clothes steamer</a></li><li><strong>Best travel clothes steamer </strong>- <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Tefal-Compact-Perfect-Handheld-Clothes/dp/B0BX7166HT?tag&#61;telegraphaffiliate-21&amp;ascsubtag&#61;customid-21&amp;th&#61;1" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Tefal Pure Pop</a></li><li><strong>Best looking clothes steamer </strong>- <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.johnlewis.com/steamery-cirrus-no-3-garment-steamer/sand/p110433423" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Steamery Cirrus 3 Iron Steamer</a></li><li><strong>Best folding clothes steamer </strong>- <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.johnlewis.com/philips-sth3000-26-handheld-foldable-garment-steamer/p6218245" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Philips 3000 Series Handheld Steamer</a></li></ul><hr /><h2 class="u-heading-size-medium u-heading-style-normal">Is a clothes steamer worth it?</h2><p>Absolutely, says <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://www.fashionstylist.uk/" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Emma Lightbown</a>, fashion stylist of 12 years for Gymshark and other brands. There are so many fabrics in our wardrobes that benefit from having a steamer rather than an iron. They are much more effective on pleated skirts and dresses and on tricky-to-iron areas like frills and gathered or puffed shoulders.</p><p>Retail expert and founder of <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://currentboutique.com/" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Current Boutique</a> Carmen Lopez agrees, saying, A clothes steamer is definitely worth the investment. First, its easier to use a steamer than an iron. They can help eliminate odours and refresh clothing between washes. She uses her steamer for wrinkle removal in delicate silks and cashmere as well as cotton, linen and wool.</p><h2 class="u-heading-size-medium u-heading-style-colour">How we tested the best clothes steamers</h2>
  
