<div class="component article-body-text    " data-test="article-body-text">
  
  

	

	
	

	
	



  
  
    <ul><li>1500W power</li><li>280ml water tank</li><li>20 second heat-up</li><li>1.1kg weight</li></ul><p><em>Reviewed by Simon Lewis</em></p><p>Cadrim is a small company that started out making beauty products and their steamer was recommended to me by a beautician friend. She said it changed her life after years battling with spitting, underpowered handheld steamers that leave watermarks on your clothes.</p><p>The Cadrim heats up quickly, with a light that tells you when its ready to use (never longer than 20 seconds) and the jet is noticeably stronger than most other steamers on test. There are two simple settings: trigger-activated and continuous steam. It can last over 20 minutes in trigger-activated mode and about half that in continuous. The reason for the long run-time is the big, 280ml tank. That does make it a big unit, though  more than twice the size of the Philips, below  so its best suited for home use.</p><p>Lots of steamers have a brush head, but this one also has a lint remover head - useful when steaming wool, velvet, gaberdine and other materials that tend to attract fluff and hair.</p><p>It falls down slightly when used horizontally: the steam holes are quite large, so you get a certain amount of dribbling. But we have this on permanent standby for freshening up clothes that come out of the wardrobe wrinkled. It doesnt look bad standing on the sideboard either.</p>
  
