			</span>
		

		
		
	</figcaption>



	

	
	


</figure>
<div class="articleBodyText section">




<div class="component article-body-text    " data-test="article-body-text">
  
  

	

	
	

	
	



  
  
    <ul><li>1500W power</li><li>300ml water tank</li><li>1.4kg weight</li></ul><p><em>Reviewed by Simon Lewis</em></p><p>It would be hard to choose between this and the Cadrim, which has similar power and capacity. You might be swayed by the British brand name (Swan is a 100 year-old Midlands manufacturer) but like most of the others, its actually made in China. Like the Cadrim, it has a lockable trigger for continuous steam and a particularly decent brush head.</p><p>The ceramic faceplate with multiple holes makes it almost as good as the Russell Hobbs for horizontal use, but my favourite feature is the turbo steam function, which is noticeably more effective than the others on stubborn creases in linen and stiff cotton. It uses up water much more quickly, but to compensate, the Swan has the biggest tank of them all.</p><p>If the compact Philips is the Danny DeVito of garment steamers, this is the Arnold Schwarzenegger. (Yes, I did watch Twins recently.)</p><p><strong>In the same range:</strong></p><p>If youre not into size, Swan also do a <a class="ck-custom-link" href="https://shop.swan-brand.co.uk/products/swan-foldable-garment-steamer" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">foldable steamer</a> with the same amount of power but a much smaller (120ml) tank.</p>
  
</div>
</div>
